item.title: As Arab States Recognize Israel, Egypt's 'Cold Peace' Points to Challenges Ahead
item.description: Egypt was the first Arab country to recognize Israel more than 40 years ago, but the relationship shows the challenges of translating government ties into grass roots goodwill.

item.title: U.S. Economic Momentum Eases While Europe Steadies
item.description: The U.S. economy lost a bit of pace in December as it endured a rise in virus infections, while the easing of virus restrictions in Europe helped shore up its economy.

item.title: Brexit Negotiations Inch Forward---With One Key Obstacle
item.description: Negotiators moved closer to an agreement on the future relationship between the U.K. and European Union, officials from both sides said, though they remained far apart on a major stumbling block: access by EU boats to British waters.

item.title: Biden's Win Gives Ireland Deep-Rooted Ally
item.description: The president-elect’s ascent could provide Ireland with a boost on the world stage amid Brexit negotiations and efforts to revive the global economy.

item.title: Paris Is Fined for Breaking France's Gender Rules---by Hiring Too Many Women
item.description: The city government of Paris has been dealt an unlikely punishment: a fine of about $110,000, for appointing too many women to senior positions and breaking France’s gender-equality rules.

item.title: EU Unveils Plans to Help Banks Clean Up Soured Covid-19 Loans
item.description: The European Union unveiled plans to assist countries in setting up a network of national “bad banks” to help cope with a possible avalanche of defaulted loans triggered by the pandemic.
